  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Option C, \"An assessment process that systematically overvalues inexpensive properties and undervalues expensive properties\", seems the most unfair. Two important factors are that $[1]$ inexpensive properties tend to belong to poorer people and expensive properties tend to belong to more affluent people, and $[2]$ property taxes are based on a property's value. Given this, systematically overvaluing inexpensive properties while undervaluing expensive properties not only causes one group to be unfairly charged more property tax (proportionally) than another, but the group that is being overtaxed is the one on whom over taxation would be most detrimental (since they are most likely the least capable of paying extra costs)! This scenario is far more unfair than Option D, since over taxation for the rich would probably be more of an inconvenience rather than detrimental."
